+=  is an operator which  adds and assigns the value on the right of the operator to the value on the left of the operator. 
So, lines two and three in the following code snippet are the same:

int value = 0;
value = value + 5;
value += 5;

Console.WriteLine(value);

output.
10

Example 2
int value = 1;

value++;

++value; // Ethier side of ++ would be the increment of the variable

Console.WriteLine(value);


Output.
3


Example 3


int value =1 ;

value = value +1;

Console.WriteLine($"Value of Frist number: {value}");

value ++;

Console.WriteLine("Value of Second number: "+ value);


value += 1;
Console.WriteLine("Value of third number: "+ value); // left side value will be added to right side variable.

value -= 1;
Console.WriteLine("Value of forth number: "+ value); // left side value will be deducted to right side variable.



value --;
Console.WriteLine("Value of Fifth number: " + value); 

Output
Value of Frist number: 2
Value of Second number: 3
Value of third number: 4
Value of forth number: 3
Value of Fifth number: 2


Example 4

//Position the increment and decrement operators

int value = 1;
value++;
Console.WriteLine("First: " + value);
Console.WriteLine($"Second: {value++}");
Console.WriteLine("Third: " + value);
Console.WriteLine("Fourth: " + (++value));

output
First: 2
Second: 2
Third: 3
Fourth: 4

